rst Brownlow Medalist]]\n[[File:Luke Darcy.jpg|thumb|upright|Leigh Matthews Trophy winner Luke Darcy]]\n* [[Allan Hopkins]] (1930)\n* [[Norman Ware]] (1941)\n* [[Peter Box]] (1956)\n* [[John Schultz (footballer, born 1938)|John Schultz]] (1960)\n* [[Gary Dempsey (Australian footballer)|Gary Dempsey]] (1975)\n* [[Kelvin Templeton]] (1980)\n* [[Brad Hardie]] (1985)\n* [[Tony Liberatore]] (1990)\n* [[Scott Wynd]] (1992)\n* [[Adam Cooney]] (2008)\n<small>Note: [[Chris Grant (footballer)|Chris Grant]] gained the most votes in 1997 but was not eligible to win the award due to suspension</small>\n\n===Norm Smith Medal winners===\n{{Main|Norm Smith Medal}}\n* [[Jason Johannisen]] (2016)\n\n===Leigh Matthews Trophy winners===\n{{Main|Leigh Matthews Trophy}}\n* [[Luke Darcy]] (2002, with [[Michael Voss]])\n\n===Coleman Medal winners===\n{{Main|Coleman Medal}}\n*[[Jack Collins (footballer, born 1930)|Jack Collins]] (1957)\n*[[Kelvin Templeton]] (1978, 1979)\n*[[Simon Beasley]] (1985)\n\n===Club awards===\n{{Main|Charles Sutton Medal}}\nThe Charles Sutton Medal is awarded annually to the Bulldogs player adjudged [[best and fairest]] over the entire AFL season. \nOther club awards include the:\n* Doug Hawkins Medal (awarded to the runner-up in the best and fairest count)<ref name=\"B&F\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2016-10-05/sutton-medal-winner|title=Bontempelli caps stunning season with Sutton Medal|date=5 October 2016|publisher=westernbulldogs.com.au}}</ref>\n* Gary Dempsey Medal (awarded to third place in the best and fairest count)<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* Scott West Most Courageous Player<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* Chris Grant Best First Year Player<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* Brad Johnson Best Team Player<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* Tony Liberatore Most Improved Player<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* John Schultz Community Award<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* Victoria University Education Award<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* John Van Groningen Domestique Award<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* Footscray Best and Fairest (awarded to the best and fairest player in the VFL competition)<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* Bulldogs Taskforce VFL Coaches Award<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n* Best in Finals \u2013 only awarded in years when Bulldogs play in the finals<ref name=\"B&F\"/>\n\n==Reserves team==\nIn 1925, the year Footscray was admitted to the VFL, the club's reserves team began competing in the Reserves Grade competition. The team won six premierships between 1925 and 1999. Following the demise of AFL reserves competition in 2000, the reserves team was dissolved and a [[Australian Football League reserves affiliations|reserves affiliation]] was established with the new [[Victorian Football League]]'s two western clubs: [[Werribee Football Club|Werribee]], from 2001 to 2007, and [[Williamstown Football Club|Williamstown]], from 2008 until 2013.\n\nAfter a fifteen-year recess, the club re-established a stand-alone reserves team to compete in the [[Victorian Football League]] from 2014 onward.<ref>[http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2013-10-14/dogs-name-footscray-vfl-coach Western Bulldogs VFL team]</ref> Known as the Footscray Bulldogs, the team plays its home games at [[Whitten Oval]].<ref>[http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2013-08-16/footscray-bulldogs-to-play-at-victoria-university-whitten-oval- Footscray Bulldogs to play at Victoria University Whitten Oval]</ref> The team has since won two VFL premierships, in its first and third seasons of competition.<ref>{{cite web|title=Footscray comes from three goals down to claim VFL premiership by 22 points over Box Hill|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/footscray-comes-from-three-goals-down-claim-vfl-premiership-by-22-points-over-box-hill/story-fni5fazt-1227065722018|work=Herald Sun|date=21 September 2014|author=Staff}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"6\"|'''Premierships (8)'''\n|-\n!Year\n!Competition\n!Opponent\n!Score\n!Venue\n|-\n| [[1936 VFL season|1936]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne]] || '''15.11 (101) \u2013 6.14 (50)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1945 VFL season|1945]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]] || '''9.16 (70) \u2013 9.3 (57)''' || [[Victoria Park, Melbourne|Victoria Park]]\n|-\n| [[1962 VFL season|1962]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] || '''13.13 (91) \u2013 10.8 (68)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1988 VFL season|1988]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] || '''17.14 (116) \u2013 14.12 (96)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1994 AFL season|1994]] || [[Victorian State Football League|AFL Reserves (VSFL)]]|| [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] || '''16.16 (112) \u2013 13.14 (92)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1998 AFL season|1998]] || [[Victorian State Football League|AFL Reserves (VSFL)]]|| [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]] || '''20.16 (136) \u2013 12.8 (80)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[2014 VFL season|2014]] || [[Victorian Football League|VFL]]|| [[Box Hill Football Club|Box Hill]] || '''16.13 (109) \u2013 13.9 (87)''' || [[Docklands Stadium]]\n|-\n| [[2016 VFL season|2016]] || [[Victorian Football League|VFL]]|| [[Casey Scorpions]] || '''13.19 (97) \u2013 10.6 (66)''' || [[Docklands Stadium]]\n|}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"6\"|'''Runners-up (5)'''\n|-\n!Year\n!Competition\n!Opponent\n!Score\n!Venue\n|-\n| [[1938 VFL season|1938]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Geelong Football Club|Geelong]] || '''12.8 (80) \u2013 12.19 (91)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1955 VFL season|1955]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Richmond Football Club|Richmond]] || '''9.12 (66) \u2013 13.18 (96)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1974 VFL season|1974]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]] || '''16.12 (108) \u2013 26.13 (169)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1977 VFL season|1977]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Richmond Football Club|Richmond]] || '''10.15 (75) \u2013 19.18 (132)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n| [[1986 VFL season|1986]] || [[Victorian State Football League|VFL Reserves]]|| [[Carlton Football Club|Carlton]] || '''10.12 (72) \u2013 22.14 (146)''' || [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==AFL Women's team==\n[[File:Western Bulldogs 04.03.17.jpg|thumb|The team is led through the banner by vice-captain [[Ellie Blackburn]] in round 5, 2017]]\n\nIn June 2013, the Western Bulldogs fielded a [[women's Australian rules football|women's football]] side against {{AFLW Mel}} in the first AFL-sanctioned women's exhibition match, held at the MCG. The two teams competed annually over the next three years for the Hampson-Hardeman Cup.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Twomey|first1=Callum|title=First bounce for women's footy at the MCG|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2013-06-24/first-bounce-for-women|accessdate=16 October 2016|publisher=AFL.com.au|date=16 October 2016}}</ref> In 2016, when the AFL announced plans for [[AFL Women's]], an eight team national women's league competition, the Bulldogs were asked to submit an application for a license alongside other AFL clubs.<ref name=NWL>{{cite news|title=Women's team can be next generation heroes: Stevenson|url=http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2016-05-02/womens-team-can-be-next-generation-heroes-stevenson|accessdate=16 October 2016|work=Western Bulldogs|publisher=Bigpond|date=2 May 2016}}</ref> The club was one of four Melbourne-based clubs to be granted a license that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bulldogs awarded inaugural license in National Women's League|url=http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2016-06-15/bulldogs-receive-womens-team-license|accessdate=16 October 2016|work=Western Bulldogs|publisher=Bigpond|date=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe club's first players were marquee signings [[Katie Brennan]] and [[Ellie Blackburn]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Brennan, Blackburn revealed as Bulldogs women's team marquee players|url=http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2016-07-27/brennan-blackburn-revealed-as-dogs-marquees|accessdate=16 October 2016|work=Western Bulldogs|publisher=Bigpond|date=27 July 2016}}</ref> They were joined in August by priority player [[Emma Kearney (sportswoman)|Emma Kearney]] who had previously worked in an off-field role at the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kearney chosen as Dogs' priority player|url=http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2016-08-25/kearney-chosen-as-dogs-priority-player|accessdate=16 October 2016|work=Western Bulldogs|publisher=Bigpond|date=25 August 2016}}</ref> In October, the club completed its inaugural playing list by adding 22 other senior listed and two rookie players in [[2016 AFL Women's draft|the league's draft and signing period]]. Former Monash Blues ([[Victorian Amateur Football Association|VAFA]]) coach [[Paul Groves (Australian coach)|Paul Groves]] was named as the team's first head coach and football manager in August 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmook|first1=Nathan|title=Paul Groves appointed women's head coach|url=http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2016-08-23/groves-appointed-womens-head-coach|accessdate=16 October 2016|publisher=AFL.com.au|date=23 August 2016}}</ref> The following month, the club signed three-year sponsorship agreements with [[Priceline (Australia)|Priceline]], [[Bob Jane T-Marts]] and [[Pancake Parlour]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Iconic brands named Women's Team partners|url=http://www.westernbulldogs.com.au/news/2016-09-03/iconic-brands-named-womens-team-partners|accessdate=16 October 2016|work=Western Bulldogs|publisher=Bigpond|date=3 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe team's training base and administrative headquarters are located alongside the men's team at the Whitten Oval, and as part of the initial application, it plans to play home games at Whitten Oval, [[Eureka Stadium]] and Docklands Stadium.<ref name=NWL/> The club has also fielded a team in the second-tier [[VFL Women's]] league since 2016, the league's inaugural year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vfl.com.au/clubs/vfl-womens-clubs/western-bulldogs/|title=Western Bulldogs|work=VFL.com.au}}</ref>\n\n{| style=\"margin-right:4px; margin-top:8px; float:right; border:1px #000 solid; border-radius:8px; background:#fff; font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n| width=200 | [[2018 AFL Women's Grand Final]]||''G'' || ''B'' || ''Total''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | '''Western Bulldogs''' || '''4''' || '''3''' || '''27'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | {{AFLW Bri}} || 3 || 3 || 21\n|-\n| Venue: [[Princes Park (stadium)|Ikon Park]]\n| colspan=3 | crowd: 7,083\n| colspan=3 |\n|}\n\n===Current squad===\n{{Western Bulldogs AFL Women's current squad}}\n\n===Season summaries===\n'''AFL Women's'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%\"\n! colspan=\"9\" | Western Bulldogs AFLW honour roll\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%;\"\n! Season !! Final position\n!Coach\n!Captain!! Best and fairest !! Leading goal kicker\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|[[2017 AFL Women's season|2017]]\n|6th \n|[[Paul Groves (Australian coach)|Paul Groves]]\n|[[Katie Brennan]]\n|[[Ellie Blackburn]] & [[Emma Kearney (sportswoman)|Emma Kearney]]\n|[[Ellie Blackburn]] (6)\n|-\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|[[2018 AFL Women's season|2018]]\n|'''[[2018 AFL Women's Grand Final|Premiers]]'''\n|[[Paul Groves (Australian coach)|Paul Groves]]\n|[[Katie Brennan]]\n|[[Emma Kearney (sportswoman)|Emma Kearney]] (2)\n|[[Brooke Lochland]] (12)\n|-\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|[[2019 AFL Women's season|2019]]\n|8th ^\n|[[Paul Groves (Australian coach)|Paul Groves]]\n|[[Katie Brennan]] & [[Ellie Blackburn]]\n|[[Monique Conti]]\n|[[Katie Brennan]] (6)\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|[[2020 AFL Women's season|2020]]\n|TBC\n|[[Nathan Burke]]\n|TBC\n|TBC \n|TBC\n|}\n<small>^ Denotes the ladder was split into two or more conferences. Figure refers to the club's overall finishing position that season.</small>\n\n'''VFL Women's'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%\"\n! colspan=\"9\" | Western Bulldogs VFLW honour roll\n|- style=\"background:#bdb76b;font-size: 87%;\"\n! Season !! Final position\n!Coach\n!Captain!! Best and fairest !! Leading goal kicker\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|2016\n|6th \n|[[Debbie Lee]]\n|[[Bree White]]\n|[[Bree White]]\n|[[Alexandra Quigley]] (25)\n|-\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|2017\n|6th\n|[[Debbie Lee]]\n|[[Bree White]]\n|[[Bree White]]\n|[[Alyssa Mifsud]] (12)\n|-\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|2018\n|6th\n|[[Debbie Lee]]\n|''None''\n|[[Naomi Ferres]]\n|[[Alyssa Mifsud]] (7)\n|-\n|-style=\"font-size: 87%;\"\n|2019\n|''[[List of VFL Women's premiers|Runners-up]]''\n|[[Sean Kavanagh (coach)|Sean Kavanagh]]\n|[[Mickayla Ward]]\n|[[Ellie Gavalas]]\n|[[Danielle Marshall]] & [[Mickayla Ward]] (10)\n|}\n<small>Sources: [https://vfl.com.au/western-bulldogs-womens-historical-data/ Club historical data] and [http://websites.sportstg.com/comp_info.cgi?c=1-118-0-518546-0&pool=1001&round=0&a=STATS VFLW stats]</small>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''A History of the Footscray Football Club: Unleashed'', by John Lack, Chris McConville, Michael Small and Damien Wright. Aus-Sport Enterprises Pty Ltd, 1996 {{ISBN|0-646-26215-7}}\n*{{cite thesis |last=Nicholson|first=Matthew|date=August 2002|title=Print Media Representation of Crisis Events in Australian Football|type=PhD|chapter=Fightback: The Footscray Football Club's Fight to Survive in 1989|publisher=Victoria University|url=http://vuir.vu.edu.au/344/1/06chapter5.pdf|access-date=9 February 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|Australia}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [[2009 Western Bulldogs season]]\n* [[2010 Western Bulldogs season]]\n* [[2011 Western Bulldogs season]]\n*[[:Category:Western Bulldogs players|List of Western Bulldogs/Footscray players]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://westernbulldogs.com.au/ Official website of the Western Bulldogs]\n* [http://www.aroundthegrounds.bellestorie.com/western/western.html \"Around the Grounds\" \u2013 web documentary \u2013 Western GO DOGGIES]\n\n{{Western Bulldogs}}\n{{VFL/AFL premiers}}\n{{Australian Football League}}\n{{AFL Women's}}\n{{VFL}}\n{{VFL Women's}}\n{{Melbourne Sports Teams}}\n\n[[Category:1883 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football clubs in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Former Victorian Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1883]]\n[[Category:Western Bulldogs]]\n", "name_user": "Global-Cityzen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason summaries:2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Bulldogs"}
{"title_page": "Furlough", "text_new": "{{About||the 2018 American film|Furlough (film)}}\nA '''furlough''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|\u025cr|l|o\u028a}}; from {{lang-nl|verlof}}, \"[[leave of absence]]\") is a temporary leave of employees due to special needs of a company or employer, which may be due to economic conditions at the specific employer or in the economy as a whole. These involuntary furloughs may be short or long term, and many of those affected may seek other temporary employment during that time.\n\n== United States ==\n\n=== US federal government ===\nIn the United States, involuntary furloughs concerning federal government employees may be of a sudden and immediate nature. Such was the case in February 2010, when a single [[United States Senate]] objection prevented emergency funding measures from being implemented. As a result, 2,000 federal workers for the [[USDOT|Department of Transportation]] were immediately furloughed as of March 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2010/03/sen-bunning-singlehandedly-causes-2000-federal-worker-furloughs.html |title=Sen. Bunning Single-handedly Causes 2,000 Federal Worker Furloughs|publisher=Blogs.abcnews.com |date=2010-03-01 |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref>  The [[United States federal government shutdown of 1995 and 1996|2nd-longest such shutdown was December 16, 1995, to January 6, 1996]], which affected all non-essential employees, shutting down many services including [[National Institutes of Health]], visa and passport processing, parks, and many others. This happened again on October 1, 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rules.house.gov/archives/98-844.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-22 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050928010223/http://www.rules.house.gov/archives/98-844.pdf |archivedate=September 28, 2005 }}</ref> and on January 19, 2018.\n\nThe United States Congress failed to pass a re-authorization of funding for the [[Federal Aviation Administration]], and as a result, furloughed about 4,000 workers at midnight on July 22, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fedsmith.com/2011/07/22/faa-furlough-nearly-4000-employees/|title=FAA to Furlough Nearly 4,000 Employees|last=Smith|first=Ian|website=FedSmith.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Potential furlough in 2011 ====\nCongress was on the verge of forcing a [[Government shutdown#Potential government shutdown of 2011|government shutdown on April 8, 2011]], if their plan to reduce the federal budget deficit was not resolved, which would have caused the furlough of 800,000 out of two million civilian federal employees.<ref>{{cite news|author=Charles Riley, staff reporter |url=http://money.cnn.com/2011/04/06/news/economy/federal_workers_shutdown/index.htm |title=Shutdown: 800,000 federal workers in the dark|publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2011-04-06 |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704013604576246612535953974 |title=Government Prepares for Shutdown |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=2011-04-06 |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Furloughs in 2013 ====\n{{main|United States budget sequestration in 2013|2013 United States federal government shutdown}}\nThe first federal government furloughs of 2013 went into effect as a result of [[budget sequestration]] (or sequester) \u2013 the automatic spending cuts in particular categories of federal outlays.  (This procedure was first used in the [[Gramm\u2013Rudman\u2013Hollings Balanced Budget Act]] of 1985.)  The sequesters were designed to take place if the [[federal deficit]] exceeded a set of fixed deficit targets. In 2013 specifically, sequestration refers to a section of the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]] (BCA) that was initially set to begin on January 1, 2013, as an [[austerity]] [[fiscal policy]]. These cuts were postponed by two months by the [[American Taxpayer Relief Act of 2012]] until March 1, when this law went into effect.  At that time, most federal departments and agencies began furloughing their employees in order to meet their spending cut targets. For the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]], almost all of the civilian workforce as well as most full-time, dual-status military technicians of the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] and the Reserves were affected. The initial furlough requirement was 176 working hours per affected employee, which was later cut to 88 hours.  Due to cost-cutting measures in other areas, this furlough was further reduced to a total of 48 working hours per [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] civilian and full-time Reserve Component member.\n\nLater, on October 1, 2013, at 12:01&nbsp;am&nbsp;EDT, Congress' inability to agree on a spending bill led to a government shutdown. During the shutdown, most \"non-essential\" government employees were furloughed.  This resulted in approximately 800,000 government workers being put on a leave beginning October 1. Congress later unanimously voted to restore pay to the furloughed workers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Korte, Gomez|first=Gregory, Alan|title=Congress likely to restore pay for furloughed workers|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2013/10/05/congress-shutdown-furloughed-pay/2926887/|publisher=USA Today|date=October 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/29/us/politics/federal-agencies-lay-out-contingency-plans-for-possible-shutdown.html |title=Federal Agencies Lay Out Contingency Plans for Possible Shutdown |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 28, 2013 |access-date = 5 March 2020|first1=Michael S. |last1=Schmidt |first2=Thom |last2=Shanker |first3=Andrew |last3=Siddons}}</ref>\n\n==== Furloughs in 2018 and 2019====\n{{Main|2018\u201319 United States federal government shutdown}}\n\nDue to the government shutdown starting on December 22, 2018, approximately 350,000 federal employees were furloughed for 35 days until January 25, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/09/shutdowns-economic-damage-1-billion-a-week-1071609|title=Shutdown\u2019s economic damage: $1 billion a week|last=Guida|first=Victoria|date=January 9, 2019|website=Politico|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Furloughs in 2020 in the United States ====\nIn September 2019 the [[United States Department of Labor]] issued [https://www.dol.gov/agencies/whd/fact-sheets/70-flsa-furloughs Fact Sheet #70 governing furloughs]. These rules have remained in place (as of March 21, 2020), but with new developments in connection with the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]], new rules and guidance could be issued at any time. The [[United States Department of Labor]] has a [https://www.dol.gov/coronavirus Coronavirus Resources] page which can be consulted for the latest developments.\n\n=== Schools ===\nBoard members of various school districts as well as universities implemented \"furlough days\" in 2009. This made students pay the same rate, if not more for their education while providing fewer educational days by forcing educators and staff members to take the day off.  In states such as [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], the [[Georgia Board of Regents|Board of Regents]] of the [[University System of Georgia]] included a clause so that mandatory furlough days are implemented but no classes are lost during the 2009\u20132010 academic year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usg.edu/hr/news/furlough_information/ |title=Furlough Information - Human Resources|publisher=University System of Georgia |date= |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn [[California]], the State Employee Trades Council (SETC) voted to implement a mandatory two-day-per-month furlough policy for the staff and faculty of the [[California State University|CSU]] system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/PA/News/2009/setc2.shtml |title=Members of State Employees Trades Council Ratify Tentative Agreement for 2009-2010 &#124; CSU &#124; Public Affairs |publisher=Calstate.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref>  The furloughs, intended to prevent layoffs, began in August 2009, and ended in June 2010.  The 10% cut saved about $270 million of the CSU's $564 million budget deficit.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fontana |first=Cyndee |url=http://www.modbee.com/2010/07/18/1257752/furloughs-over-for-schools-in.html |title=Furloughs over for schools in the CSU - Education |publisher=The Modesto Bee |date=July 18, 2010 |accessdate=2013-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005015250/http://www.modbee.com/2010/07/18/1257752/furloughs-over-for-schools-in.html |archivedate=2013-10-05 }}</ref>\n== United Kingdom ==\n\nThe word ''furlough'' was first defined officially in the UK on March 24, 2020 in response to the [[Covid-19]] pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-employers-and-businesses-about-covid-19/covid-19-support-for-businesses|title=UK Gov: COVID-19: support for businesses|website=[[GOV.UK]]|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> The government announced a new ''Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme'' to enable businesses to continue paying part of their employees\u2019 salary for those that would otherwise have been laid off.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: support for businesses |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-employers-and-businesses-about-covid-19/covid-19-support-for-businesses |website=[[GOV.UK]] |publisher=[[Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy]] |accessdate=26 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200326123547/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-employers-and-businesses-about-covid-19/covid-19-support-for-businesses |archivedate=26 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Private sector ==\nDuring the [[Great Recession|global recession of 2009]] companies such as [[Intel]], [[Toyota]], and [[Gannett]] implemented furloughs.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Employee Furloughs Can Be a Bad Alternative to Layoffs\n|url=http://www.ere.net/2009/02/09/employee-furloughs-can-be-a-bad-alternative-to-layoffs/\n|website=ERE.net\n|date=February 9, 2009\n|accessdate=October 8, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the US federal government shutdown of 2013 federal contractors such as [[Lockheed Martin]] and [[United Technologies]] considered furloughing their own employees.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2013/10/07/united-technologies-lockheed-martin-revise-furloug.aspx\n|title=United Technologies, Lockheed Martin Revise Furlough Plans After Pentagon Brings Workers Back\n|website=The Motley Fool\n|date=October 7, 2013\n|accessdate=October 8, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, retail giants, [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/30/coronavirus-macys-will-furlough-most-employees-beginning-this-week.html including Kohl\u2019s and Macy\u2019s], furloughed thousands of employees because of decreased sales connected to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].\n\n==Other uses==\nThe term furlough in employment can also refer to [[annual leave]], [[long service leave]], time off based on a company-planned schedule. For example, with a \"work three weeks, off one week\" schedule, a company's workforce is divided into four groups. Each group, in turn, takes a week off on furlough while the remainder work. It can also refer to a vacation from [[missionary work]], [[leave (military)|military leave]], or, in the case of convicts, [[parole]], [[probation]], [[conjugal visit]], or [[work release]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{wiktionary}}\n* [[Four-day week]]\n* [[Layoff]]\n* [[Short time]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{NIE Poster}}\n* [https://www.opm.gov/furlough/ Guidance and Information on Furloughs] from the [[United States]] [[Office of Personnel Management]].\n* [http://www.salon.com/2006/05/26/askthepilot187/ Furlough: The worst cockpit terror of them all! What if it happens to you?] by [[Patrick Smith (columnist)|Patrick Smith]], May 26, 2006.\n* [http://money.cnn.com/2009/03/11/news/economy/furloughs/index.htm?postversion=2009031104 CNNMoney special report: Enjoy your forced vacation], March 11, 2009.\n\n{{Employment}}\n\n[[Category:Leave]]\n[[Category:Working time]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the 2018 American film|Furlough (film)}}\nA '''furlough''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|\u025cr|l|o\u028a}}; from {{lang-nl|verlof}}, \"[[leave of absence]]\") is a temporary leave of employees due to special needs of a company or employer, which may be due to economic conditions at the specific employer or in the economy as a whole. These involuntary furloughs may be short or long term, and many of those affected may seek other temporary employment during that time.\n\n== United States ==\n\n=== US federal government ===\nIn the United States, involuntary furloughs concerning federal government employees may be of a sudden and immediate nature. Such was the case in February 2010, when a single [[United States Senate]] objection prevented emergency funding measures from being implemented. As a result, 2,000 federal workers for the [[USDOT|Department of Transportation]] were immediately furloughed as of March 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2010/03/sen-bunning-singlehandedly-causes-2000-federal-worker-furloughs.html |title=Sen. Bunning Single-handedly Causes 2,000 Federal Worker Furloughs|publisher=Blogs.abcnews.com |date=2010-03-01 |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref>  The [[United States federal government shutdown of 1995 and 1996|2nd-longest such shutdown was December 16, 1995, to January 6, 1996]], which affected all non-essential employees, shutting down many services including [[National Institutes of Health]], visa and passport processing, parks, and many others. This happened again on October 1, 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rules.house.gov/archives/98-844.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-22 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050928010223/http://www.rules.house.gov/archives/98-844.pdf |archivedate=September 28, 2005 }}</ref> and on January 19, 2018.\n\nThe United States Congress failed to pass a re-authorization of funding for the [[Federal Aviation Administration]], and as a result, furloughed about 4,000 workers at midnight on July 22, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fedsmith.com/2011/07/22/faa-furlough-nearly-4000-employees/|title=FAA to Furlough Nearly 4,000 Employees|last=Smith|first=Ian|website=FedSmith.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Potential furlough in 2011 ====\nCongress was on the verge of forcing a [[Government shutdown#Potential government shutdown of 2011|government shutdown on April 8, 2011]], if their plan to reduce the federal budget deficit was not resolved, which would have caused the furlough of 800,000 out of two million civilian federal employees.<ref>{{cite news|author=Charles Riley, staff reporter |url=http://money.cnn.com/2011/04/06/news/economy/federal_workers_shutdown/index.htm |title=Shutdown: 800,000 federal workers in the dark|publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2011-04-06 |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704013604576246612535953974 |title=Government Prepares for Shutdown |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=2011-04-06 |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Furloughs in 2013 ====\n{{main|United States budget sequestration in 2013|2013 United States federal government shutdown}}\nThe first federal government furloughs of 2013 went into effect as a result of [[budget sequestration]] (or sequester) \u2013 the automatic spending cuts in particular categories of federal outlays.  (This procedure was first used in the [[Gramm\u2013Rudman\u2013Hollings Balanced Budget Act]] of 1985.)  The sequesters were designed to take place if the [[federal deficit]] exceeded a set of fixed deficit targets. In 2013 specifically, sequestration refers to a section of the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]] (BCA) that was initially set to begin on January 1, 2013, as an [[austerity]] [[fiscal policy]]. These cuts were postponed by two months by the [[American Taxpayer Relief Act of 2012]] until March 1, when this law went into effect.  At that time, most federal departments and agencies began furloughing their employees in order to meet their spending cut targets. For the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]], almost all of the civilian workforce as well as most full-time, dual-status military technicians of the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] and the Reserves were affected. The initial furlough requirement was 176 working hours per affected employee, which was later cut to 88 hours.  Due to cost-cutting measures in other areas, this furlough was further reduced to a total of 48 working hours per [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] civilian and full-time Reserve Component member.\n\nLater, on October 1, 2013, at 12:01&nbsp;am&nbsp;EDT, Congress' inability to agree on a spending bill led to a government shutdown. During the shutdown, most \"non-essential\" government employees were furloughed.  This resulted in approximately 800,000 government workers being put on a leave beginning October 1. Congress later unanimously voted to restore pay to the furloughed workers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Korte, Gomez|first=Gregory, Alan|title=Congress likely to restore pay for furloughed workers|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2013/10/05/congress-shutdown-furloughed-pay/2926887/|publisher=USA Today|date=October 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/29/us/politics/federal-agencies-lay-out-contingency-plans-for-possible-shutdown.html |title=Federal Agencies Lay Out Contingency Plans for Possible Shutdown |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 28, 2013 |access-date = 5 March 2020|first1=Michael S. |last1=Schmidt |first2=Thom |last2=Shanker |first3=Andrew |last3=Siddons}}</ref>\n\n==== Furloughs in 2018 and 2019====\n{{Main|2018\u201319 United States federal government shutdown}}\n\nDue to the government shutdown starting on December 22, 2018, approximately 350,000 federal employees were furloughed for 35 days until January 25, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/09/shutdowns-economic-damage-1-billion-a-week-1071609|title=Shutdown\u2019s economic damage: $1 billion a week|last=Guida|first=Victoria|date=January 9, 2019|website=Politico|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Furloughs in 2020 in the United States ====\nIn September 2019 the [[United States Department of Labor]] issued [https://www.dol.gov/agencies/whd/fact-sheets/70-flsa-furloughs Fact Sheet #70 governing furloughs]. These rules have remained in place (as of March 21, 2020), but with new developments in connection with the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]], new rules and guidance could be issued at any time. The [[United States Department of Labor]] has a [https://www.dol.gov/coronavirus Coronavirus Resources] page which can be consulted for the latest developments.\n\n=== Schools ===\nBoard members of various school districts as well as universities implemented \"furlough days\" in 2009. This made students pay the same rate, if not more for their education while providing fewer educational days by forcing educators and staff members to take the day off.  In states such as [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], the [[Georgia Board of Regents|Board of Regents]] of the [[University System of Georgia]] included a clause so that mandatory furlough days are implemented but no classes are lost during the 2009\u20132010 academic year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usg.edu/hr/news/furlough_information/ |title=Furlough Information - Human Resources|publisher=University System of Georgia |date= |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn [[California]], the State Employee Trades Council (SETC) voted to implement a mandatory two-day-per-month furlough policy for the staff and faculty of the [[California State University|CSU]] system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/PA/News/2009/setc2.shtml |title=Members of State Employees Trades Council Ratify Tentative Agreement for 2009-2010 &#124; CSU &#124; Public Affairs |publisher=Calstate.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-10-07}}</ref>  The furloughs, intended to prevent layoffs, began in August 2009, and ended in June 2010.  The 10% cut saved about $270 million of the CSU's $564 million budget deficit.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fontana |first=Cyndee |url=http://www.modbee.com/2010/07/18/1257752/furloughs-over-for-schools-in.html |title=Furloughs over for schools in the CSU - Education |publisher=The Modesto Bee |date=July 18, 2010 |accessdate=2013-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005015250/http://www.modbee.com/2010/07/18/1257752/furloughs-over-for-schools-in.html |archivedate=2013-10-05 }}</ref>\n== United Kingdom ==\n\nThe word ''furlough'' was first defined officially in the UK on 24 March 2020 in response to the [[Covid-19]] pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-employers-and-businesses-about-covid-19/covid-19-support-for-businesses|title=UK Gov: COVID-19: support for businesses|website=[[GOV.UK]]|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> The government announced a new ''Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme'' to enable businesses to continue paying part of their employees\u2019 salary for those that would otherwise have been laid off.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: support for businesses |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-employers-and-businesses-about-covid-19/covid-19-support-for-businesses |website=[[GOV.UK]] |publisher=[[Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy]] |accessdate=26 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200326123547/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-employers-and-businesses-about-covid-19/covid-19-support-for-businesses |archivedate=26 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Private sector ==\nDuring the [[Great Recession|global recession of 2009]] companies such as [[Intel]], [[Toyota]], and [[Gannett]] implemented furloughs.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Employee Furloughs Can Be a Bad Alternative to Layoffs\n|url=http://www.ere.net/2009/02/09/employee-furloughs-can-be-a-bad-alternative-to-layoffs/\n|website=ERE.net\n|date=February 9, 2009\n|accessdate=October 8, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the US federal government shutdown of 2013 federal contractors such as [[Lockheed Martin]] and [[United Technologies]] considered furloughing their own employees.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2013/10/07/united-technologies-lockheed-martin-revise-furloug.aspx\n|title=United Technologies, Lockheed Martin Revise Furlough Plans After Pentagon Brings Workers Back\n|website=The Motley Fool\n|date=October 7, 2013\n|accessdate=October 8, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, retail giants, [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/30/coronavirus-macys-will-furlough-most-employees-beginning-this-week.html including Kohl\u2019s and Macy\u2019s], furloughed thousands of employees because of decreased sales connected to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].\n\n==Other uses==\nThe term furlough in employment can also refer to [[annual leave]], [[long service leave]], time off based on a company-planned schedule. For example, with a \"work three weeks, off one week\" schedule, a company's workforce is divided into four groups. Each group, in turn, takes a week off on furlough while the remainder work. It can also refer to a vacation from [[missionary work]], [[leave (military)|military leave]], or, in the case of convicts, [[parole]], [[probation]], [[conjugal visit]], or [[work release]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{wiktionary}}\n* [[Four-day week]]\n* [[Layoff]]\n* [[Short time]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{NIE Poster}}\n* [https://www.opm.gov/furlough/ Guidance and Information on Furloughs] from the [[United States]] [[Office of Personnel Management]].\n* [http://www.salon.com/2006/05/26/askthepilot187/ Furlough: The worst cockpit terror of them all! What if it happens to you?] by [[Patrick Smith (columnist)|Patrick Smith]], May 26, 2006.\n* [http://money.cnn.com/2009/03/11/news/economy/furloughs/index.htm?postversion=2009031104 CNNMoney special report: Enjoy your forced vacation], March 11, 2009.\n\n{{Employment}}\n\n[[Category:Leave]]\n[[Category:Working time]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited Kingdom:Date style = make consistent with the rest of the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlough"}
{"title_page": "Candy Pangilinan", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2011}}\n{{Philippine name|Pangilinan}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image =\n| name                    = Candy Pangilinan\n| birthname               =\n| birth_date              = {{birth date and age|1972|5|8}}\n| birth_place             = [[Metro Manila]], [[Philippines]] \n| death_date              =\n| death_place             =\n| nationality = [[Philippines|Filipino]]\n| occupation              = Actress, comedian\n| years_active            = 1991\u2013present \n| children                = 1\n| agent = [[GMA Artist Center]]<br />[[Viva Entertainment]]<br />[[Regal Entertainment]]<br />[[Star Cinema]]<br />[[Star Magic]]<br />[[TV5 (Philippines)|Talent5]]\n}}\n\n'''Candy Pangilinan ''' (born May 8, 1972) is a Filipino film and television [[actress]] and [[comedian]]. She won best actress for CineFilipino 2016 and Los Angeles International Film Festival for the movie ''Star na si Van Damme''.\n\n==Biography==\nIn the early 1990s, she starred in supporting roles in romantic comedy films such as \"Hindi Magbabago\" with [[Carmina Villaroel]] in 1994 and 1997, ''Dahil Ba Sa Kanya'' as a lead role alongside [[Aga Muhlach]], [[Mikee Cojuangco-Jaworski]] and [[Onemig Bondoc]] and \"Sige Subukan Mo\" with [[Ace Vergel]] and [[Maricel Soriano]]. 1998 in \"Kung Ayaw Mo Huwag Mo\" her second time working with Maricel Soriano and [[Jolina Magdangal]], \"Honey, Nasa Langit Na Ba Ako\" with [[Regine Velasquez]] and in 2000 in \"Ayos Na Ang Kasunod\" with [[Fernando Poe, Jr.]] and [[Ara Mina]]. In 2007, she was cast in a comedy film ''[[Apat Dapat, Dapat Apat]]'' with friends and comedians [[Rufa Mae Quinto]], [[Pokwang]], [[Eugene Domingo]], produced by Quinto with Viva Films and ON Q-28 Productions. In television, she is known for her role in the series ''[[Mula Sa Puso]]'' until its finale in 1999 she then played side kick to [[Claudine Barretto]]'s character Rosario in ''[[Saan Ka Man Naroroon]]'' in 1999 to 2001. ''[[I Love Betty La Fea]]'' from 2008 to 2009 with a follow up on the Philippine remake of ''[[Only You (2009 TV series)|Only You]]'' with [[Angel Locsin]], [[Sam Milby]] and [[Diether Ocampo]] on [[ABS-CBN]] and the Critically Acclaimed Series ''[[Minsan Lang Kita Iibigin]]'' in 2011, in 2012 she did supporting roles for [[GMA Network]] such as ''[[Forever (Philippine TV series)|Forever]]'' with [[Heart Evangelista]], [[Geoff Eigenmann]] and [[Gloria Romero (actress)|Gloria Romero]], and ''[[Hiram na Puso]]'' with [[Gina Alajar]] and [[Kris Bernal]], she then did notable guest appearances on the hit Saturday trivia-game show ''[[Celebrity Bluff]]'' alongside [[Eugene Domingo]] in 2013. In 2014, she guest starred on [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]] on ''[[Sharon (talk show)|Sharon]]'', ''[[Sharon: Kasama Mo, Kapatid|Kasama Mo Kapatid]]'', ''[[Beki Boxer]]'', ''Regal Shocker Presents'', ''[[Showbiz Police]]'', ''[[Face the People]]'' and ''Tropa Mo Ako Unli''. In ''[[Wansapanataym]]'', the revived TV series back in ABS-CBN in Perfecto and Noreen Capili's My App Boyfie. She is known today as one of the critically acclaimed comedians in the Philippines who has spanned more than 3 decades in the industry who also has the criteria for being known to star in more than 10 sitcoms for her versatility, wit, skill and comedy roles.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" background: #f9f9f9\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n! Year || Title || Role || Production\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Bilangin ang Bituin sa Langit (TV series)|Bilangin ang Bituin sa Langit]] || Connie Herrera || [[GMA Network]]\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Make It with You (TV series)|Make It with You]] || Mariel Dimaguiba (Billy's Mother) With [[Enrique Gil]] and [[Liza Soberano]] || [[ABS-CBN]] \n|-\n| 2019 || [[Dragon Lady]] || Mimi || rowspan=2 | [[GMA Network]]\n|-\n| 2018-2019 || [[My Special Tatay]] || Chona Mariano\n|-\n| 2018 || [[Precious Hearts Romances Presents]]: [[Araw Gabi]